## QA Gate — the commit cycle (QA-1, QA-2)

Full detail in `QA_GATE_CHECKLIST.md`. The non-negotiable shape:

```
code → tests → panel → fix → tests → panel → (repeat until clean) → commit
```

- **Tests are part of the deliverable (QA-2).** Write them in the *same change* as the
  code, never "later." Every new gate gets one test entering at the public entry point that
  asserts the gate fired. Every new enum/format gets one load→process→output test.
- **The review panel runs *before* the commit (QA-1), not after.** A review after commit is
  documentation, not quality control. Tier the panel by risk (see checklist) so it's cheap
  on low-risk diffs and thorough on auth/DB/agent-write diffs.
- **Integration tests hit real DB/APIs where possible (FAIL-3).** No mock-only coverage of
  a write path. Signature-enforced doubles only (`create_autospec` in Python; typed doubles
  in TS) — a bare mock that accepts any signature hides drift for months.
- **Write the regression test before the fix (FAIL-5).** A fix isn't done until a test fails
  before it and passes after, entering at the public entry point.
- **Mutation-test the logic core (QA-6).** Line coverage is execution, not verification. Run
  Stryker / `mutmut` on the business-logic core with a mutation-score floor; a surviving mutant
  is a test that asserts nothing. Don't trust an after-the-fact or LLM-written test until a
  mutant dies for it.
- **An oracle for non-deterministic output (QA-7).** For any model-backed / probabilistic
  output, assert a **metamorphic relation** (more duration ⇒ strictly more calories) instead of
  an exact string, and **fuzz the untrusted input boundary** (fast-check / Hypothesis). See
  `scaffold/tests/metamorphic.example.test.ts`.

